  "datePublished": "2025-12-26",
  "description": "An open set is a subset of a topological space that belongs to the space\u0026rsquo;s topology. In the standard topology on R\\mathbb{R}, the open interval (0,1)(0, 1) is open — every point inside it has some breathing room, a little interval around it that stays entirely within the set. The closed interval [0,1][0, 1] is not open, because the endpoints 0 and 1 have no room to spare: every interval around 0 includes negative numbers that lie outside [0,1][0, 1].\n",
